  "companies": [],
  "statement": "# Merge k Sorted Lists\n\nGiven an array of sorted linked-list heads, return one sorted list containing all nodes.\n\n## Examples\n\n**Example 1**\n\n```text\nInput: lists = [[-5,2,9],[-4,3],[0,8]]\nOutput: [-5,-4,0,2,3,8,9]\n```\n\n**Example 2**\n\n```text\nInput: lists = []\nOutput: []\n```\n\n**Example 3**\n\n```text\nInput: lists = [[],[1]]\nOutput: [1]\n```\n\n## Constraints\n\n- The judge provides a `ListNode` class with `val` and `next` fields.\n- Node values fit in normal signed integer range.\n- The total number of nodes across one test case is kept small enough for local execution.",
  "editorial": "Push each non-empty list head into a min-heap. Repeatedly pop the smallest node and push its successor.",
  "solution_notes": "```python\nimport heapq\n\nclass Solution:\n    def mergeKLists(self, lists):\n        heap = []\n        for index, node in enumerate(lists):\n            if node:\n                heapq.heappush(heap, (node.val, index, node))\n        dummy = ListNode(0)\n        tail = dummy\n        counter = len(lists)\n        while heap:\n            _, _, node = heapq.heappop(heap)\n            tail.next = node\n            tail = tail.next\n            if node.next:\n                counter += 1\n                heapq.heappush(heap, (node.next.val, counter, node.next))\n        return dummy.next\n```",
  "hints": [
    "Only the current head of each list can be the next smallest node.",
    "A heap keeps that choice efficient."
  ],
  "starter_code": {
    "python": "class Solution:\n    def mergeKLists(self, lists):\n        pass\n"
  },
  "entrypoint": {
